EASTERN EQUINE ENCEPHALITIS - NORTH AMERICA (05): USA (MASSACHUSETTS)
*********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 3 Aug 2020 4:16 PM EDT
Source: Taunton Gazette [edited]
https://www.tauntongazette.com/news/20200803/middleboro-resident-positive-for-eastern-equine-encephalitis-virus/1


A Middleboro resident is the 1st person to test positive for the eastern equine encephalitis virus this year [2020] in Massachusetts.

Town Manager Robert G Nunes said the Massachusetts Department of Public Health [DPH] informed the town of a human case on Monday afternoon [3 Aug 2020].

"We just received notice from the MASS DPH that a human case of EEE/West Nile has been reported in Middleboro," he wrote in a Facebook post.

The Department of Public Health on Monday afternoon [3 Aug 2020] announced that a Plymouth County resident between the ages of 11 and 20 tested positive for the eastern equine encephalitis virus and is presenting meningoencephalitis, which is inflammation of the brain caused by an infection.

The state health department, by practice, doesn't identify victims by name or give the specific city or town they live in.

Nunes said Middleboro has banned all outdoor activities on town property from dusk to dawn.

State health officials raised the risk level for the eastern equine encephalitis virus to high in Middleboro and Carver last Wednesday [29 Jul 2020] due to several mosquitoes carrying the disease [virus] being detected in the towns.

In Massachusetts this year [2020], 29 mosquitoes have tested positive for the eastern equine encephalitis virus and 20 for the West Nile virus.

In Middleboro, 6 mosquitoes with the eastern equine encephalitis virus have been trapped.

[Byline: Cody Shepard]

