Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The human case of eastern equine encephalitis (EEE) appeared about 3 weeks after the virus was found in mosquitoes for the 1st time this year (2020). EEE virus has been detected in Plymouth (where the human case occurred) and Franklin Counties for the 1st time this year and for the 3rd time in Massachusetts, the Department of Public Health announced Wednesday (15 Jul 2020). Last year (2019) was an unusually active year for EEEV transmission in the eastern USA, with cases in humans and horses, including in Massachusetts. As mentioned in many previous ProMED-mail posts, horse owners in eastern and upper midwestern USA states should vaccinate their animals now if they have not done so already. There is no commercially available vaccine for humans, so avoidance of mosquito bites is the only preventive measure to take.

Additional information on EEE is available on the CDC website at https://www.cdc.gov/EasternEquineEncephalitis/. - Mod.TY

